Much of good police work depends on patience, tolerance, and common sense. These are traits and characteristics that one learns in time \emdash  through experience, trial and error, and by observing others. There are few people \emdash  and even fewer books \emdash  that can teach these hard-to-define qualities. In police training as we know it there is no class or course entitled \ldblquote Common Sense\rdblquote . It's something all good policemen just \ldblquote have\rdblquote . Some are blessed with a greater measure of it than others, and thus may achieve and succeed quicker than their peers. \par
Many times our success can be measured best in terms of good luck rather than good management. When we handle a situation just right or defuse a volatile incident as if by magic, we can take credit for a job well done: but do we really know how we did it? \par
Terry Barker is a consultant, lecturer and teacher. He has worked closely with policemen for over fifteen years. He knows better than most about how policemen actually think and act. His subject is communications skills, and his method is parable.  That is, he tells stories. His students learn by relating to tales and scenarios. With Terry Barker as the story teller, learning becomes easy and entertaining. \par
In his book, The Five Minute Policeman, Terry has put common sense into a tangible form. He has made common sense something that can actually be grasped and identified. As the pages of this book turn, not only will you learn a new system, and see how and why it works, but also you'll be able to identify how and why some of your own methods have worked for you in the past. Instead of having a situation turn for the better next time by good luck, Terry will have given you \ldblquote The System\rdblquote  \emdash  the tools with which you can achieve the same results by design. The ability to deal with the public in all its forms, moods and temperament with a \ldblquote System\rdblquote  allows even experienced policemen to feel a new confidence; and we all know that confidence coupled with experience and ability means a polished and professional job. \par
Enjoy The Five Minute Policeman and give Terry's \ldblquote System\rdblquote  a try. It will prove to be one of your most valued tools. \par
Sgt. W. E. (Ed) Hill NCO i/c RCMP Detachment Gibsons Gibsons, B.C. December 12, 1988. \par
