\b Bad day at the office \par
\b0 The Sergeant calls me in, and I can tell from the way he invites me to close the door that he wants me to volunteer for something I'm going to regret. His body language always telegraphs his mood: when he's going to tear strips off, he closes the door himself. No, that's not right \emdash  he slams it. But when he means to be subtle, and get you to offer your bod for some task you're going to hate yourself for in the morning, he remembers what he learned on the Police Managers' Course and gets you to shut it. I'm sure of it when he waves me to the corner chair instead of the across-the-desk one. \par
\ldblquote Matt,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote I've got a little problem I want you to help me with.\rdblquote  \par
After 18 years in the Force I've learned that the \ldblquote Sergeant's Little Problem\rdblquote  usually means the \ldblquote Constable's Big Disaster\rdblquote . \ldblquote I'm pretty busy these days,\rdblquote  I say, \ldblquote what with the manpower shortage, the paper work, and the \emdash  \rdblquote\par
 \ldblquote Yeah, yeah. I know. But this is special. Matt, you're the only one who can do this job. Your experience. Your communication skills. Your System. Matt, I want you to partner up with Burns.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Tacky Burns?\rdblquote  \ldblquote No, not Tacky, it's Jim \emdash  Jim Burns. Where do you guys get this \lquote Tacky\rquote  stuff, anyways?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Search me,\rdblquote  I say. \ldblquote It's his nickname. He won't discuss it \emdash  makes a bit of a mystery out of it, actually. Sometimes he gets called The Tack, or just plain Tack.\rdblquote  \par
I could have mentioned that the sergeant has a nickname too. The guys call him Zorro \emdash  because of how he slashes their reports to pieces with a red pen. He sure as hell wouldn't want to hear that though, so I go on about Tacky Burns: \par
\ldblquote I guess he picked it up somehow, like everyone does,\rdblquote  I say. \par
\ldblquote He's knocked around for enough years. Personally, I think a more appropriate name for him would be \lquote Grunt\rquote . Or maybe \lquote Animal\rquote . Hey, come on, Sarge, what have I ever done to you to deserve this? Burns is a savage.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote I want you to start tomorrow, Matt,\rdblquote  he says, looking out the window and ignoring my comment. \par
\ldblquote I want you to educate him. Teach him The System \emdash  all those great people skills of yours. Help him learn to deal with the complainants and drunks and crotchety old folks, all that routine stuff that he always screws up and you never do. I admit that he's great in a pinch, but how much of your career is spent in pinches? Jim Burns is a diamond in the rough, Matt: I want you to polish him.\rdblquote  \par
Diamond in the rough, yeah. But there are some other adjectives that come to mind: like crude, rude, coarse, gamy, gross, uncouth, crass, vulgar, and \emdash  primitive. That's the one that fits best. Tacky Burns is a Neanderthal. A throw-back to the dawn of time. \par
\ldblquote He has a gift,\rdblquote  the sergeant continues reflectively, \ldblquote for turning minor problems into major situations. When he sees a brush fire he throws gasoline on it. Perfectly nice people foam at the mouth when they talk about him. Believe me, I spend a lot of time trying to smooth waters he has troubled. It's time something was done.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote But, Sergeant \emdash  \rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Start tomorrow, Matt. Teach him The System.\rdblquote  \par
\par
Tacky Burns slides in beside me and says, \ldblquote Putting on weight again, eh, Matt? Think there's room for both of us in the front seat? Eh? Eh? Shit! Jeez, I didn't know I'd be sharing a car with a eggplant.\rdblquote  Eggplant? \par
 He has an eye for the jugular, The Tack has. It's true that I've gained a few pounds around the middle, but only someone with less sensitivity than a tub of buttocks would actually mention it. Sam, my ex-wife, used to refer to me as a bald stork wearing glasses. Or, occasionally, six feet of string with a knot in the middle. I didn't appreciate her jokes much but even they were preferable to eggplant. \par
I say, \ldblquote Tack, did the sergeant say anything to you about why he partnered us up?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Yeah. He says you're going to teach me people skills.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote How do you feel about it?\rdblquote  \par
The Tack looks me in the eye and says, \ldblquote Hey, what difference does it make, how I feel? There's only one way to deal with people, man \emdash  pow, right in the kisser. Shit. Most people are pond scum, that's how I feel. Anyway, what's wrong with the way I do my job? It's worked OK for me so far, ain't it?\rdblquote  \ldblquote You think this is going to be a pointless exercise?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote It's all pensionable time, man,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote If the sergeant wants me to drive around with you and learn to be a fuckin bleeding heart social worker \emdash  well, that's OK with me.\rdblquote  \par
I think about Tacky Burns. He's a seven year member with a good reputation for being there when you need him, and a bad reputation for too much drinking and a negative attitude. He hangs out with some of our more cynical brethren and has been known to start more than his share of fights after imbibing too much at \ldblquote choir practices\rdblquote , which he attends religiously. I scan him out of the corner of my eye. I see a stocky white male about five eleven, probably weighing in at a little over two hundred. He always needs a shave: cursed by a Nixon beard, he has a permanent all-day five o' clock shadow. What do I know about my new partner? For one thing, I know he's the office arm-wrestling champ. For another, he's a better than average hockey enthusiast. I classify myself as a pretty dedicated sports fan, but The Tack can recite detailed stats about hockey players so obscure that I never even heard of them. He tells the funniest war stories and the filthiest dirty jokes. He's a happy drunk, even in a fight: when he's on the floor nursing a bloody nose, he's laughing at the same time. He drives a muscle car that he maintains himself. He won't let even a skilled professional mechanic touch it. He models himself on the Sixties TV cop, Kojak. He watches NYPD Blue and yells out loud when they bag a bad guy. He loves the \ldblquote Police Academy\rdblquote  movies but he doesn't realize that they're supposed to be comedy. He dislikes female members, though he admits they're useful for strip searches and admin. He's what they call a man's man, and a lot of the guys look up to him. He's married and has a family, but never mentions them. He doesn't bring them to any of our functions. We've never met his wife or his kids. He doesn't participate in the incessant bragging that we all do about our bright, strong, obedient and perfect children, and our beautiful, intelligent wives.  \par
I ask around and come up with some facts and opinions. He was born in a small Manitoba town twenty-seven years before. His father named him James William, after his own father, who came from the U.K. Father and grandfather were both silent by nature. His mother, Olga Sophie, spoke little English. Thus young James William Burns (aka \ldblquote Tacky\rdblquote ) was raised in a painfully silent environment where the most sparkling dinner conversation consisted of \ldblquote Pass the salt\rdblquote . His father ran the town hardware store. Young Jim helped out from age seven, learning how to talk to the customers (\ldblquote Got a number two file?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yep.\rdblquote  \ldblquote How much?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Two bucks.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Gimme one.\rdblquote ) He worked in his father's store for two years after graduating from high school. Then he decided to become a police officer. When asked why, he shrugs and says things like, \ldblquote I was bored.\rdblquote  Sometimes he says he doesn't know. Once he let on that he \ldblquote wanted to do high speed car chases.\rdblquote  There is a story that he gained the nickname in police academy because he once bought up all the sticky buns and tried to \ldblquote merchandise\rdblquote  them to the other guys. The nickname began as \ldblquote Sticky\rdblquote  but changed to \ldblquote Tacky\rdblquote  because it was a \ldblquote tacky\rdblquote  thing to do. I doubt that this is true. \par
What I do not doubt is that he learned at the Academy \emdash  selectively learned, that is \emdash  that there are only two kinds of people \emdash  police officers and jerks. He graduated from the Academy with average marks. He spent his first couple of years on general duty and traffic patrol. He learned to take the heat for senior members' mistakes. His trainer in the crucial first six months was a burnout named Dozer Dempster who taught Tacky how to sing in the choir, avoid work, and above all dominate and scare hell out of the jerks. \par
Tack's favourite example of \ldblquote jerk-hood\rdblquote  is a raving drunk blaming the other driver as police are digging bodies out of the wreckage. Another: a rapist explaining that it was his victim's fault for wearing a tight dress. Yet another: a molester virtuously justifying himself while you try to comfort an abused child. His world is full of pond scum. After seven years, The Tack has learned that when the phone rings it's always bad news. He is cynical, hardened, belligerent, aggressive and abrasive \emdash  the very qualities demonstrated by the police officers he most admires \emdash  and he's content to be that way. He feels unappreciated by the Force. Others get good assessments, cushy courses, neat jobs; he is passed by. Those who get promoted are wimps in his book. They are the kind of members who seldom get involved in confrontations the way he does. He thinks they are cowards. He does not see a promotion in his own future. He resents jerks calling about barking dogs and noisy parties when he has all this paper work to do. He isn't good at paper work \emdash  spelling and grammar are not his strong suits \emdash  and when jerks bother him with trivia it means staying late to struggle with the typewriter. So he is short with them. To cut short the time you must spend dealing with jerks \emdash  be short yourself! \par
Once he attended a communication course for constables with me. He said it was all a lot of bull. His buddies said so too. And the ones who didn't say so were jerks. He survives each day by being aggressive or indifferent with the public, convinced it's the only way (there's only one way, man; POW, right in the kisser). His tone of voice is flat and unfriendly. His body language is cold and aloof.  And this is the guy Sarge wants me to teach The System to \emdash  a guy with the verbal skill than a pile of wet underwear, and about as much personal warmth as a dead cow. \par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  I finally say, \ldblquote let's get going.\rdblquote  I put the car in gear and we drive down Lake Street. I don't have much hope for this enterprise, but if this is what Sarge wants me to do, here goes. \par
\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  I start, \ldblquote let's talk about your run-in with Mrs. O'Brian last Thursday.\rdblquote  \par
\par
But before we get a chance to talk about Mrs. O'Brian, we're responding to a complaint. Two men are reported to be publicly boozing it up and playing rowdy music in a small neighbourhood park up in the Gerrold Heights area. You should know that Gerrold Heights is a ritzy section of town, up in the hills above the orchards and the lake. The view is terrific, though the folks who live there are not. Most of them are professional people, managers, owners of big companies, or simply retired after a life of successful and undetected crime. No one else could afford one of these homes, let alone pay the wages it must take to pay the staff required just to maintain the grounds. Or serve them tea in the drawing room. Hell, I wouldn't even be able to pay the taxes. We drive to the complainant's home. Surprise, surprise. It's a colonial mansion with stone pillars and a white crushed oyster-shell driveway. What was I expecting, a hut? The complainant looks like a retired British Army colonel \emdash  a bluff, hearty, ruddy-complexioned man with a generous white moustache, a robust build, and a snotty foghorn voice. Then I think to myself that this guy's no colonel. Anyone who lives in a place like this needs a lot more than a military pension, just to service the interest on the mortgage. But regardless of his history, he's a man used to being obeyed. And right now he's royally pissed off. \par
\ldblquote Those men down there,\rdblquote  he shouts, pointing to a small park three-quarters enclosed by the houses at the end of the cul-de-sac. \ldblquote They've been disturbing the peace! Drinking beer and playing loud music in full view of the houses here! What an example for our youth!\rdblquote  I case the area and wonder how many children there might be. Not many. This street is Terminal Row. Nobody lives here under age ninety-five.\par
\ldblquote I insist that you go down there and arrest them,\rdblquote  he says. \par
So I tell the colonel we'll check the situation out, and we cruise on down to the park. \par
\ldblquote Lemme handle this one,\rdblquote  says the Tack. \ldblquote You aren't the only one around here who knows how to handle routine cases. Lemme show you how I deal with them.\rdblquote  \par
Without waiting for an answer, he sashays over to a laurel hedge where two men of dark complexion are sitting on a blanket. One of them has a guitar, which he puts down as we approach. \ldblquote Good evening, officers,\rdblquote  he says politely in what might be a Portuguese accent. The Tack gives me a look as if to say, Now watch me do some real stuff here. \par
 Then he turns to the two and barks, \ldblquote Don't gimme none a that Good evenin shit!\rdblquote  He looms over them like Godzilla. \ldblquote You jerks have been drinking beer in a public place contrary to statute, and disturbing the peace.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote But sir,\rdblquote  Guitar Man says, \ldblquote we are not drinking alcoholic beverages.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote If you rub sand in my ointment,\rdblquote  Tacky says, \ldblquote I'll do the Virginia Reel on your head.\rdblquote  He waggles his baton threateningly around in the air. \par
\ldblquote Now lemme see those cans.\rdblquote  He points to some aluminum cans partly concealed under the blanket.\par
\ldblquote Certainly, sir,\rdblquote  Guitar Man says, and tugs at the edge of the blanket. Out come the cans. The labels read: DIET PEPSI The Tack looks a bit stressed, but he's still running on a full tank of adrenalin. \par
\ldblquote OK,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote so maybe you weren't drinking. But we got a complaint from the neighbours here that you were sure as hell disturbing the peace.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote But, Officer,\rdblquote  says Guitar Man politely, \ldblquote how could we be doing that? No. We were just quietly singing some old country folk songs. We have no amplifying equipment. No one could hear us from the sidewalk, let alone in any of those houses. I assure you, sir, we have not done anything wrong.\rdblquote  \par
At this point The Tack should admit that he blew it and pull out. But his ego has taken a beating. This is the famous \ldblquote Short Fuse\rdblquote  Burns we're talking about here, remember. He loses his cool completely, switches into his Mad Dog persona, and pulls out his cuffs. \par
\ldblquote I should bag you guys for loitering,\rdblquote  he yells. But now Guitar Man is getting mad too. \par
\ldblquote I want your name!\rdblquote  he demands. \ldblquote What's your badge number! I have friends at City Hall! I'll see to it that you'll spend the rest of your career on garbage detail!\rdblquote  \par
I soothe the man and drag The Tack away before he can make an even bigger fool of himself than he already has. We leave the park in disgrace and drive around the block. We park. \ldblquote Asshole,\rdblquote  The Tack says, referring to Guitar Man. \par
\ldblquote Why do you call him an asshole ?\rdblquote  I ask. \par
\ldblquote He's guilty as shit.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Of what?\rdblquote  I demand. \par
\ldblquote Sitting in the park? Playing his guitar? Drinking Pepsi, for God's sake?\rdblquote  \par
Tack has the decency to look abashed. \par
\ldblquote OK,\rdblquote  he says at last. \ldblquote So how would you have handled it?\rdblquote  \par
This would be the right moment to teach Tack about The System, but there's a tap on the car window. A trendy kid of maybe eleven or twelve is leaning his mountain bike against the fender, watching us. He taps again. \par
\ldblquote Hey,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote you guys are parked in a no parking zone. I thought cops were supposed to obey the law. Great example you set for us kids.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Bug off, rodent,\rdblquote  Tacky growls, \ldblquote or I'll send your parts home to your Dad in a flat envelope.\rdblquote  This is too much for me. My job is to teach this ox, but not to let him trash my beat. So I interrupt and say, \par
\ldblquote Hey, kid, what's your name?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote What's it to you?\rdblquote  he says, offended. \par
\ldblquote Just wondered,\rdblquote  I say. \par
\ldblquote My name's Matt. Don't pay any attention to my partner here \emdash  he's had a bad day. Hop in and I'll show you how the siren works.\rdblquote  \par
The kid gives me the careful once-over, but after a while he lets on that his name is John. Then he jumps into the back seat and I show him where all the controls are. I even bop the siren for him briefly. Five minutes later he decides to become an officer when he grows up. He yells his thanks as he pedals off. \ldblquote Waste of time, being nice to kids,\rdblquote  The Tack says. \ldblquote Give em half a chance, they'll knife you in the old wazoo.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Now you listen to me,\rdblquote  I lecture him. \ldblquote Kids today are on the razor's edge. How we treat them decides what kind of adults we'll have to deal with in a few years. If we can get them on our side now \emdash  and it's pretty easy to do, it doesn't take much time or energy \emdash  we've got supporters for life. Listen, when I wade into a pub fight ten years from now that kid might be there to back me up. All because instead of putting him down with a \i bug off\i0  I showed some interest.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote You're a damn social worker,\rdblquote  The Tack says. \par
\ldblquote It's not social work. It's officer survival.\rdblquote  \par
He stubbornly clams up. End of dialogue. At our station, Sarge has a sacred rule that we have to obey even if it costs us a coffee break. It's called NOTIFICATION OF COMPLAINANT. Whenever a complainant calls, we have to report back later and let them know how things turned out. Sarge says it's the cheapest and easiest kind of PR there is; it costs only a few minutes but it pays huge dividends in public support. And even though I do find it a bit of a personal nuisance some times, I have to agree with him. It really does pay off. \par
\ldblquote Let's get back and notify the complainant,\rdblquote  I say. \par
\ldblquote Come on, Matt, lemme do it, eh?\rdblquote  Tacky says. \ldblquote I admit I screwed up before, but lemme try again, OK? I can be tactful when I have to be.\rdblquote  \par
I shrug: Why not? After all, how much trouble can he get into over a simple notification? I soon learn. \par
We mosey back to the Colonel's mansion.  The Tack doesn't ring the bell like normal people do: instead, he raps his baton smartly on the door. I can hear it echoing inside. It sounds like the clap of doom. The Colonel whaps open the door and his mouth at the same time: \ldblquote Those men are still down there in my park!\rdblquote  he hollers. \ldblquote I thought I told you to go down and arrest them!\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  Tacky says, practicing tact, \ldblquote let's just cool down here. They aren't actually doing anything I can arrest them for.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote What? Are you saying that you don't believe me? I've told you that those men were drinking and disturbing the peace. Now haul your asses down there and truck them away! My taxes pay your salary!\rdblquote\par
But Tacky has heard that one once too often. His body language becomes aggressive and electric. His face flushes, his shoulders hunch, he leans forward, and he sticks his finger in the Colonel's face. The hell with tact. \ldblquote Listen here, Asshole,\rdblquote  he snaps, \ldblquote you probably don't even pay taxes, for Chrissake. All you rich guys have a free ride. What do you do for a living, peddle smack?\rdblquote  I fear that the Colonel is going to have a coronary right there on his doorstep, so I move in fast. \ldblquote What my partner means to say,\rdblquote  I say smoothly, \ldblquote is that of course we're certainly here to protect you. There is nothing so annoying as people disturbing the peace. We'll be glad to arrest those men.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  the Colonel says, \ldblquote that's more like it!\rdblquote   \ldblquote We really appreciate it when people have enough public spirit to call on us in matters like this. However, we do have a problem here.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Problem? What damn problem!\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote The problem as I see it,\rdblquote  I say, \ldblquote is that (as my partner here has pointed out) we don't have any evidence. There's no booze bottles, nothing on their breath. So if we do arrest them, how do we make it stick?\rdblquote  He glares at me. \ldblquote However,\rdblquote  I go on, \ldblquote there is a way....\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  he demands, \ldblquote what is it?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote If you'd be willing to testify in court that you actually were disturbed....?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote What, me go to court?\rdblquote  he says. \par
\ldblquote I realize that it's an imposition to ask someone as busy as yourself to attend court, but as you pointed out earlier, you do pay the taxes that pay our wages, and that's a kind of a contract, isn't it? I mean, we work together to keep the streets safe for the neighbourhood kids. We arrest the bad guys, then you identify them in court and provide the evidence that puts them away. So if you're willing to play your part....\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote I don't want to go to court,\rdblquote  he says. \par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  I say, \ldblquote that does give us a problem.\rdblquote  I wait.\par
 \ldblquote Oh, hell,\rdblquote  he says at last. \ldblquote I guess it's not major enough to go through all that. Hey, listen, thanks for coming out. Nothing we can do about it? You sure?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote I guess,\rdblquote  I say, and shrug eloquently. \par
\ldblquote I think that the damn laws should have some real teeth, but I get your point \emdash  you don't make the laws, do you? Well, what the hell, thanks for coming out.\rdblquote  He goes in and shuts the door. Tack stares at me. \par
\ldblquote How did you do that?\rdblquote  he finally asks. \par
\ldblquote I used The System.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote You keep talking about The System. What system?\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Putting it positively,\rdblquote  I say, \ldblquote The System is a way of getting other people to want to do what you want them to want to do. Or, putting it negatively, it's how you tell people to go to hell so professionally that they can't wait to make the trip.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote Yeah, but how did you do it? I'd of had him in a hammerlock if you hadn't bailed me out....\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote I didn't want to have to answer to Sarge when that jerk complains about us,\rdblquote  I say. \ldblquote So it was worth spending five minutes to tranquilize him.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote My system,\rdblquote  Tacky mutters. \ldblquote is to wallop the bad guys to the floor. Make them do the chicken.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote OK \emdash  and you need that. But how much of your career is actually spent in direct physical confrontation? The average officer spends at most ten hours of his thirty year career in fighting or dodging bullets. The rest of the time is routine. Tack, if you can learn to pacify people instead of riling them up, your job gets easier. The less you have to actually do, the better.\rdblquote  \par
\ldblquote I always thought of a good officer as someone who's bigger and stronger than the guys he has to fight,\rdblquote  he says. \par
\ldblquote Yeah? Well I think a good officer is someone who's so much smarter than the bad guys that he never has to put his dukes up.\rdblquote  \par
