\ldblquote Sure. Here's Lesson One \emdash  learn to control your big ugly sarcastic mouth,\rdblquote  I say, gritting my teeth. I learned about The System myself from a friend of mine who once worked as a complaints clerk at Sears. He called it \ldblquote The Five-Fold Path\rdblquote  because it has five parts to it. I just call it \ldblquote The System\rdblquote . The job of a complaints clerk isn't so different from ours. They have to deal with people over the counter \emdash  so do we. We're in the people business too. Over the years I learned how to apply his approach to our work, and it's passed the test. It's not easy, trying to describe something as fragile as The System to Tacky Burns, but this is how the lecture goes: Police officers can use The System (I explain to Tacky) to get in and out of problem situations in five minutes or less. \par
\par
There are five clearly identifiable steps in dealing with difficult people: \par
\par
STEP ONE is to manage your own natural feelings. Most folks, when they start an interaction with police, are in a state of emotion. In other words, they may start with a short fuse or no fuse at all. When they confront you in person their very body language may tense you up even before they open their mouths: hands on hips or arms crossed, jaw thrust forward, face flushed or livid. If they're on the phone the voice is high or rapid, and they often sound abusive. The natural human response is to meet anger with anger. But our anger only fuels their anger. We have to learn to think of anger as the price of admission \emdash  in other words, anger is what we have to put up with just to do our job. Or putting it another way, other people's anger is our job. I pull out my notebook and write: 1. Control Your Anger This isn't something you can do on the spur of the moment. When some crummy teenager calls you a pig, every last gram of adrenalin naturally surges right smack to your baton hand and you want to lash out. No, you have to think it out beforehand \emdash  have a positive philosophy. A police officer, like a complaints clerk, has to understand the job as dealing with difficult people. Then once you think of it that way it's not such a shock when they behave like jerks. \par
\par
STEP TWO is to listen intently and accurately to what the other person is trying to tell you. That's not as easy as it sounds. Most of us are lousy listeners. There are two principles however, which help us not only to listen better, but also to let the other person know we're listening. The first principle is to ASK QUESTIONS. Don't take what the other person is saying for granted. You may have misunderstood, or maybe they\rquote re too discombobulated to get their facts straight. So ask clarifying questions to make sure you got the information right. The second principle is to GIVE FEEDBACK. From time to time, repeat back what you think the other person said and let them check it out. Did you hear them right? The only way you'll know is by letting them compare your interpretation with theirs. Feed back to them what you think you heard and ask them if that's what they thought you said. If you ASK QUESTIONS and GIVE FEEDBACK, you'll not only be more accurate, but also you'll defuse the other person's anger. How can they stay mad at someone who's obviously trying really hard to listen to them? \par
\par
Step Two, therefore is: 2. Listen and Check. \par
\par
STEP THREE in The System is to let the other person know that you understand how they feel.  My friend the complaints clerk said this took him longer to master than the other steps because he's the kind of guy who isn't very comfortable dealing with emotions \emdash  especially other people's. My friend wasn't comfortable expressing his own feelings, either. Ask his wife. (I was the same. You could ask Sam. She'd tell you how limited I used to be in expressing feelings. How many times did she ask me if I loved her? Why couldn't I ever tell her?) A lot of members have this problem. It comes with being macho. But the fact is that all of us, including macho police officers, operate on at least two different levels. One level is facts \emdash  what happened, who's involved, the time and date, that kind of thing. Most of us are okay with that. The other level, though, is harder. People sometimes communicate badly because they`re hurting inside. Or they're hostile. Or they're scared. Simple statements like, \ldblquote I know how it feels,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote Yeah, that must really hurt,\rdblquote  go a long way toward developing good communications on the feelings level, and it costs you absolutely nothing. For instance, after someone has told you about how the other driver came through the red light at a zillion miles an hour and barely missed them, you should not only feed back the data (make and colour of car, etc.), but also let them know you heard their feelings. Say something like, \ldblquote Boy, you must have felt like an avalanche was coming at you!\rdblquote   So Step Three is to let people know that you understand how they feel.  \i Have empathy\i0 . Now, if you've done the first three things right you've built a communications bridge between you and the other person. You've demonstrated your own willingness to listen, so they likely will reciprocate \emdash  that is, they'll listen to you. And you've shown them that you care.\par
\par
STEP FOUR is to get them on your side. You do this best by involving them in the solution to the problem. That might be as simple as just asking them to hold something, or as complex as asking for suggestions as to how to deal with a situation. People aren't hostile while they're helping. Folks returning unsatisfactory merchandise to a store don't stay mad if you ask them whether they would prefer their money back or replacement of the product. They get very upset when you try to dictate a solution to them, however. People sing the praises of police when they feel part of the action. A woman who gave coffee to some members of an emergency response team during an all-day barricade still talks about the \ldblquote nice cops\rdblquote  in a proprietary way to her friends.  If you can safely get people into things so that they feel personally involved, you move their energy around so it's with you instead of against you. \par
\par
Step Four is to: 4. Involve \par
\par
STEP FIVE is to get the show on the road. But this is a paradox. Even though the steps you've taken up till now are preparations to action, if you did them well you probably won't have to act at all. The first four steps take about five minutes. If they worked OK, then you're finished. Out. No beatings. No arrests. No jerks coming down to the station to whine about the Ugly Police Officer. On the other hand, The System isn't an excuse to walk away from your responsibilities, either. If someone complains about a loud party next door \emdash  and the officer listens well, empathizes, gets them involved, and then does nothing \emdash  he can expect complaints. \ldblquote A nice person,\rdblquote  they'll say, \ldblquote but ineffectual.\rdblquote  \par
\par
 So as the final step in The System: 5. Act \emdash  But Only If All else fails \par
\par
When I've finished telling Tacky all this, I write it down on a piece of paper and hand it to him: The System 1. Control your anger 2. Listen and check 3. Empathize 4. Involve 5. Act (if necessary!)\par
