The way I see it, there are two kinds of pot holes in the Road of Life. The first kind of pot hole is the one that all of us stumble into from time to time. We drive along just as smooth as John Doe's classic T-Bird only to find that all the time our too-perfect shocks are concealing the terrible condition of the road from us. It's full of holes, but we don't notice till it's too late. The second kind of pot hole is the kind of hole that kids hide their pot in. In one three-day period of our partnership, we run into both kinds. The Tack and I are becoming known to our peers as \ldblquote The Odd Couple\rdblquote . We're different in every way. Tack is the product of a small prairie town, while I come from an urban environment. 53 \page  The Tack's father was a practical man of few words who ran a hardware store: mine was a university professor of English, who always used twice as many words as he needed \emdash  just because he liked them. And if there was a chance to use four syllables instead of two, that was a bonus. Tack has a family: I blew mine years ago. He watches sports and cop shows on TV: I watch the PBS. We don't have much in common outside of police work. In spite of all this, as the weeks go by I find myself growing a real respect and admiration for him. Sarge called him a diamond in the rough, and he's right. He's also the salt of the earth, a pillar of the community, and a veritable Gibraltar of the Force. His honesty and integrity, blemished though they are by too many choir practices and black hangovers, impress me. There are occasions when I can't think of anyone I'd rather have at my back. Besides, he's really starting to learn and apply The System. And it's working for him. Sometimes a bit too well, as I find out on Tuesday. But three days before \ldblquote Pothole Tuesday\rdblquote , I'm invited to Tacky's house for Sunday dinner. He lives in a housing development on the west side of town, in the 'burbs. I know that he's married and has a three year old son and a daughter of eight months, but that's all I know. Even though we've been 54 \page  sharing the front seat of a cruiser for weeks, he's never discussed his private life with me. His wife, Marian, is a mouse who knows her place. She cooks up a great roast beef and Yorkshire pudding, follows it with lemon meringue pie better than my mother used to bake, and tops it all off with our choice of liqueurs in fancy boozy coffees flambeaux. I haven't eaten this well since Samantha left. \ldblquote Great stuff,\rdblquote  I tell her. \ldblquote A wonderful meal. It's a special treat for me \emdash  my cooking is absolutely degenerate.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Thank you, Matt,\rdblquote  she says, and waits for Tacky to say something. He doesn't. Finally she asks him: \ldblquote Did you like the meal, dear?\rdblquote  Tacky finishes his mouthful of Irish Coffee and says, \ldblquote I ate two helpings, didn't I?\rdblquote  This seems to satisfy her, and she goes into the kitchen to do dishes. Pot hole! I remember when Sam used to ask me the same question, and I was too dumb to realize what she really meant. She wanted to know if I appreciated her. No, that's not right \emdash  she wanted to know if I loved her. I used to answer in the same way Tacky did (I ate two helpings, didn't I?). Eventually she found someone who not only loved and appreciated her but told her so too. Right out loud. In words. 55 \page  I wish I could tell Tacky what I know about some kinds of police relationships. I wish I could advise him to abandon that silent macho ego of his when he's at home with his family. I wish I could guide his arms around that wonderful woman and teach him to say, \ldblquote You're a great person, I need you and love you.\rdblquote  I wish I could teach him to vault the barriers and run some risks. But I can't do any of those things, so I watch in mild anguish as he alternately ignores and bullies her. In my mind's eye I fantasize ten years ahead. I see her loading the furniture into a moving van, leaving him with wall to wall nothing. I watch him coming home and finding emptiness. He will ask, \ldblquote Why couldn't she have told me?\rdblquote  \emdash  but anyone whose marriage has reached the stage where one partner is contemplating decamping and absconding and the other doesn't even see it coming, is so insensitive that he deserves what he gets. Like me. Sam left me without so much as a chair to sit on. Now as I ponder what went wrong in my own marriage, I can see that Sam tried many times to talk to me. It was I who wouldn't talk, not her. I used \ldblquote confidentiality\rdblquote  as an excuse not to communicate, but in fact there were lots of things in my work day that I could have shared. 'Confidentiality' was a convenient smoke screen to hide behind. Big strong disciplined police officer. Working class hero. 56 \page  Shrunken soul. After Sam left me I started learning how to open myself up and be human, but it was too late for her and me. She's living with a teacher in the city these days, apparently quite happy, from what I hear. Well, happier than she had been with me, anyway. As I take my leave from Tacky and his mouse, I wonder how many other macho members will live through my experience, and what I could do to help. I shrug. Hell, I can't even help my own partner. On Tuesday night I hit the second pot hole. I decide that tonight I'm going to let The Tack handle things entirely on his own, even if it means letting him make a mistake. He's mastered The System to the point where I believe I can trust him. \ldblquote I really enjoyed the Sunday dinner,\rdblquote  I say as we drive up near Lake View High School. \ldblquote Marian's a great cook.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah, she is,\rdblquote  he says. The Tack parks, and we get out to have a look around. \ldblquote Tack, I know It's none of my business, but \emdash  \rdblquote  \ldblquote You're right there,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote What I mean to say is,\