ell, lads,\rdblquote  he says pleasantly, \ldblquote I guess you'd better cough up. Where is it?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Fuck you, Snotface,\rdblquote  Peter Pan sneers. The Tack is annoyed but tries to take it in his stride. \ldblquote I know how you feel,\rdblquote  he says, determined to use empathy even if it kills him. \ldblquote How the fuck would you know?\rdblquote  Peter Pan says. \ldblquote You're nothin' but a pig, and pigs don't know nothin'! Fuckin' pig! Pig! PIG!\rdblquote  Tacky wants more than anything in the world to swat these two centipedes into the ground, but holds his hand back with commendable self-discipline. Instead, he tries out his listening skills. \ldblquote Well, now,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote why would you feel that way?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Because you guys are nothin' but dog barf,\rdblquote  Bogey says. \ldblquote How would you know what it's like? I bet you never even tried a little smoke.\rdblquote  Trying to build a communications bridge, Tacky falls into Bogey's trap. \ldblquote Oh, I wouldn't say that.\rdblquote  Bogey, who might be the smarter of the two, smells blood and in he goes. \ldblquote I can't believe you ever tried it,\rdblquote  he says slyly. \ldblquote Cops are too square.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Not so,\rdblquote  Tacky responds. \ldblquote Police are like most people. We have our weaknesses.\rdblquote  \ldblquote You mean you've tried pot?\rdblquote  59 \page  Tacky now sees the abyss and pulls back from it. \ldblquote Hey, we're not talking about me,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote just police in general. There are probably some who've tried it, maybe in high school, but they stopped when they realized how harmful it is.\rdblquote  \ldblquote But they did try it in high school,\rdblquote  Bogey insists. \ldblquote Well, maybe some did, yeah.\rdblquote  \ldblquote So there you go!\rdblquote  \ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote  Tacky says. \ldblquote I mean that if you guys have tried it, how can it be so bad? I think it's just a buncha fat old baldies sittin' around desks in New York who make up these stupid laws.\rdblquote  \ldblquote New York?\rdblquote  Tacky says, puzzled. \ldblquote Well, Ottawa, or Winnipeg, or wherever the hell they make the fuckin' laws, man. The point,\rdblquote  he says, warming to his theme, \ldblquote is that anybody under thirty \emdash  and you're under thirty, right? \emdash  is sort of with it, you dig? And we can rap with each other. Right?\rdblquote  In spite of himself, Tacky is siphoned down the tubes. He retorts, \ldblquote But we can't go around breaking the law.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Sometimes you have to,\rdblquote  Bogey says. \ldblquote Look at Gandhi in Sweden, for Chrissakes, or how about the Sicks?\rdblquote  \ldblquote You mean Sikhs?\rdblquote  Tacky says, but he's blown away on a sea of rhetoric. \ldblquote Seeks, Sicks, what's the diff? The ones in Prickistan.\rdblquote  Bogey now displays his awesome grasp of world geopolitics. \ldblquote And Hitler, 60 \page  what about him? He tried to stop the Poles from tokin' up, for Chris-sakes, and they wouldn't, so he killed them all. And that's what you guys are doin, for Chrissakes. You're sendin' us to concentration camps, just like Hitler did.\rdblquote  The Tack is no intellectual, but he knows that this kid is totally screwed up. \ldblquote Hey, listen, kid,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote I'm no Hitler. Hell, my dad fought in the war against Hitler.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah? For what?\rdblquote  \ldblquote For freedom, jerk!\rdblquote  Tack says. \ldblquote Exactly my point!\rdblquote  the kid hollers triumphantly. \ldblquote For freedom! There's your old man layin' down his life for freedom for Chrissakes, and here you are, takin' it away! Why not just let people alone? What harm are we doin', anyway? You guys sneakin' around corners like fuckin' Nazis, harassin' consentin' adults, for Chrissakes, people who never did nobody any fuckin' harm. Just for usin' a natural plant a the earth, for Chrissakes. It ain't fair. You ain't fair!\rdblquote  Tacky gets so absorbed in this dialogue that he lets go of Peter Pan, who knows a good thing when he sees it. He flits quietly away into the night, abandoning his buddy to his soap box. \ldblquote Tack!\rdblquote  I say, suddenly noticing that half our bag has dropped out. \ldblquote Where's that kid?\rdblquote  The Tack whirls and flashes his light into the darkness in time to see the rear end of our prey vanishing into a hedge. Now Tacky loses his cool completely. I guess the strain of trying to be reasonable with puddle scum like these two insects is just too much for him. \ldblquote Come back here!\rdblquote  he yells at the top of his voice. But he's yelling even louder as he turns back in time to see Bogey evaporate into the night. 61 \page  We jump into the PC and start tooling around the streets, looking for Peter Pan and Bogey but without too much hope. Still, Tacky is mad enough that I hesitate to tell him that I think we should lick our wounds and forget about it. \ldblquote So much for your stupid System,\rdblquote  he says at last. He pulls over and parks. \ldblquote Doing things the old way, at least I never lost puppy snots like those guys before.\rdblquote  \ldblquote We didn't have anything on them anyway,\rdblquote  I say. \ldblquote No dope.\rdblquote  \ldblquote There was dope,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote But they got rid of it.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah. How come so fast?\rdblquote  I ask. \ldblquote Let's go back and see if we can find where they stashed it.\rdblquote  It doesn't take long to locate the loose brick in the wall. Pot hole! While we wait for the kids to return we talk about what went wrong in Tacky's dialogue with Bogey and Peter Pan. \ldblquote The problem,\rdblquote  I say, \ldblquote is that whenever you learn something new, it creates a space where nothing works very well \emdash  not the new, because you haven't got it nailed down yet, nor the old, because you've abandoned it.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah. I taught myself typing on a surplus machine my Dad brought home from the office for me \emdash  an ancient Royal. I got to be pretty good at three-finger typing. Then when I hit Grade Nine I took touch typing in school. For a while I couldn't do anything right. The old way was corrupted, and I hadn't got control over the new way.\rdblquote  \ldblquote So you lost your ability to type.\rdblquote  62 \page  \ldblquote Yeah, for a while. I wanted to quit, but the teacher asked me if I was prepared to spend the rest of my life typing with three fingers. I said no, and he said, Well that's the price you have to pay. When you learn a new system, you have to give up the old. And for a while that means you'll be less efficient.\rdblquote  \ldblquote I just wasted an hour listening to a bunch of stupid shallow teenage philosophy and got sweet nothing to show for it,\rdblquote  Tacky grits. \ldblquote Your listening skills were great,\rdblquote  I say quietly. \ldblquote Well then?\rdblquote  \ldblquote The problem wasn't your listening,\rdblquote  I say. \ldblquote It was that you argued with him.\rdblquote  \ldblquote What's the difference?\rdblquote  \ldblquote When you listen,\rdblquote  I say, \ldblquote you don't give your own opinion. You merely absorb the other person's. When you argue, you try to convince the other person that your opinion is better than theirs.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah? So what?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Arguing never did anybody a bit of good. Nobody ever convinces anyone else that their ideas are right and the other person's are wrong. When you argue, you get sucked in to a rigid pattern: first you give your opinion, then they do, then you, etc. No one listens to anyone. Everyone loses. As a police officer you can't afford to argue. You stand to lose too much. Like tonight.\rdblquote  \ldblquote I didn't see you jumping in to rescue me,\rdblquote  he says belligerently. \ldblquote In fact, I saw you just as interested in the argument as I was.\rdblquote  He's right. 63 \page  I tell myself that it was just because I wanted to hold back and leave The Tack alone, but the truth is that I really did get interested in the argument. So if Tacky was careless, I was careless, too. \ldblquote Bull,\rdblquote  I say gruffly. \ldblquote Come on, let's go. Let's quit mooching around here and go find us some action.\rdblquote  But at that moment Bogey comes slinking around the corner. We nab him with his hand in the pot hole. So our evening is not completely shot after all. Later, when I go home to my lonely apartment, I reflect on the events of the past three days. Tacky and Bogey. They have something in common. Although they're on opposite sides of the law, they're both trying to deal with a rough road by hiding something. 64 \page  Tacky's sweet mouse adores him but he treats her as if he hardly knows she's alive. He seems to cache his feelings behind a loose brick in the wall of his life. And Bogey. A smart kid on the road to catastrophe. He doesn't hide his feelings like Tacky does \emdash  just his dope. What will he be stashing behind loose bricks in a year or two? Pot holes! 65 \page  chapter seven the battle of lander house WWe all know it's coming, but nobody wants the job. Even if we don't actually have very many files going, we're all trying to look as busy as hell. When we absolutely have to be at the office, we walk around with clipboards and worried looks, make fake phone calls to non-existent sources, and work free overtime walloping keyboards. Never before have our files been so up to date. And when we are on the road, we attempt to stay out there as long as possible. Nevertheless someone has to do it, and to my dismay it turns out to be The Tack and me. The Sarge pops up just as we're going out on patrol. \ldblquote Hey, you guys,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote Come on in here.\rdblquote  Tack and I exchange mournful looks but we obey. \ldblquote I hope this won't take us too long, Sarge,\rdblquote  I say anxiously. \ldblquote We're really busy these days, what with the beach beer hall and the Biker Convention and all....\rdblquote  Actually, the beach beer hall has been pretty well tamed, and the Biker Convention is fifty miles away, and Sarge knows all this, but what the hell, it's worth a try. \ldblquote Shut the door,\rdblquote  he says affably. 66 \page  We shut it. \ldblquote Sit down.\rdblquote  He waves us to the kitty-corner seats at his desk. We sit. It does look bad. \ldblquote Smoke?\rdblquote  He offers us each one of his cheap cigars. Now I know we're in the hole. The expected conventional response to one of Sarge's rare offers is to thank him but refuse, which we always prudently do, thus permitting him the luxury of considering himself generous and gregarious; but today Tack says, \ldblquote Sure, man,\rdblquote  and lights up. I guess he figures that if we're this deep in the hole, a little deeper can't hurt. Sarge looks less than pleased, but recovers himself quickly and actually smiles. \ldblquote You fellas have been doing a great job, real great,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote So I'm going to give you a reward \emdash  a task that'll test your mettle. Something you can get your teeth into.\rdblquote  A reward? Something we can sink our teeth into? I steel myself and wait for the weenie. \ldblquote Yep,\rdblquote  he says, focusing his attention on the glowing end of Tack's cigar, \ldblquote I'm putting you guys in charge of the Lander House confrontation.\rdblquote  My heart sinks, my sphincter clenches, and I am temporarily mute. But I have to hand it to Tacky: he's really developed some great skills over the past few months. He doesn't miss a beat, just calmly looks at Sarge and says, \ldblquote That's terrific....maybe you wouldn't mind if we discussed it some?\rdblquote  67 \page  Sarge was anticipating Tacky hollering blue murder, maybe even clearing the desk with a single bound and wrapping those formidable mitts around his neck. He blinks: he is not expecting this suave response. \ldblquote Well, um, sure,\rdblquote  Sarge says. \ldblquote It's a complex matter. No piece of cake. So you have to follow instructions carefully.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah, well, see, we've been doing some thinking about this situation ourselves,\rdblquote  Tack says, settling back in his chair and blowing elegant smoke rings at the ceiling. \ldblquote In case we were lucky enough to have a chance at it, you know. We think that it has to be handled just right.\rdblquote  Hey, the only conversation we've had about the forthcoming Lander House combat was to heartily wish ourselves forty miles in the opposite direction. This is a new Tacky Burns unfolding before my very eyes. \ldblquote I'll tell you how to handle it,\rdblquote  Sarge growls. \ldblquote What you have to do is keep the protesters and the developers apart. And no matter what either of them asks you \emdash  including the damn media \emdash  you just say No Comment. I don't want you guys getting involved in the rights and wrongs of the case. You're there to protect property and make sure no one gets hurt. Got it?\rdblquote  \ldblquote I just say No Comment?\rdblquote  Tack says. \ldblquote Right.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Just \emdash  No Comment?\rdblquote  he says again. \ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  Sarge says testily. \ldblquote You got a hearing problem?\rdblquote  \ldblquote OK,\rdblquote  Tack says. \ldblquote So when the protesters ask if I'm gonna support the developers, I say No Comment. When the developers ask if I'm gonna support the protesters, I say No Comment. And when Billy Smart 68 \page  from Channel Four wants to know if the fire department and their damn hoses have really been called in, I just say No Comment. Have I got it right?\rdblquote  Sarge looks puzzled. \ldblquote It doesn't sound right,\rdblquote  he admits. \ldblquote But that is what you told me to say, right? No Comment?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah...but \emdash  \rdblquote  \ldblquote Hmmm,\rdblquote  Tack muses. \ldblquote I think I see your point, Sarge. If Billy Smart asks me about the fire department being brought in, and I say No Comment, it would sound to him like I'm really saying Yes.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah, could be,\rdblquote  Sarge concedes. \ldblquote Likewise with the other sides. If I say No Comment to the protesters, they'll think I'm siding with the developers. And if I say it to the developers, they'll put me on the protester side. Is that your point, Sarge?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah, I guess so,\rdblquote  Sarge says. \ldblquote So whoever I say No Comment to, they'll interpret it whatever way they want.\rdblquote  Sarge looks out the window. I study my fingernails. The Tack examines his cigar. \ldblquote I think we'll have to play it by ear,\rdblquote  Tacky finally says. Now Sarge looks alarmed. \ldblquote Listen,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote I've got orders from the top on this. We have to stop the violence, but we're going to be doing it in front of the cameras. I've been told to say No Comment when talking to the media. That's the policy.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah, policy,\rdblquote  Tack says, shaking his head. \ldblquote They sure know how to get your tail in a knot, don't they? Guys sitting around in an office giving orders almost like they know what's going on....\rdblquote  69 \page  We sit and ponder for a minute. \ldblquote So what do you think we should do, Sarge?\rdblquote  Tacky asks, breaking up the meditation. \ldblquote Saying No Comment is just gonna snap everyone's braces the wrong way.\rdblquote  Then Sarge says, \ldblquote Well, Tack, I guess you're just going to have to improvise. And if you can do as good a job on them as you just did on me, I think I'm safe in letting you play it your way.\rdblquote  Lander House was built in 1898, making it old enough to be a heritage building in these parts. It started as an overnight hostelry to accommodate gold-seekers on their way to the beckoning interior of the province. Errol Lander, the builder, was a young entrepreneur who could see even then that the real gold was to be found not in the beds of rivers but in the pokes of miners. His descendants have been proving him right ever since. The family motto might be: SERVICE TO GAMBLERS IS GOOD CORPORATE STRATEGY. Over the years the place grew from a simple inn to a huge rambling complex that reflected the varying architectural styles of its almost-century of life. It began as a log structure, but added a Tudor-style wing in the 20's, a glass solarium in the 30's \emdash  in which the town's most eminent citizens sipped their tea on Sunday afternoons \emdash  and an uncharacteristically hip geodesic dome in the 60's, which graced the arboretum and the extensive grounds. Quite a mixture, people said admiringly. One of a kind. 70 \page  It was a tourist attraction for many years, and a great source of civic pride. Now the latest generation of Landers had become, in the eyes of some of their neighbours at least, a degenerate lot. They wanted to sell the old place, collect their loot and take off to the Caribbean. So they quietly began talking to a big Toronto developer, one of those numbered companies without a name. By the time the project was presented to Council, all the spade-work was done, the zoning in place, and the Councillors' hands tied. So Lander House was to be obliterated and become a condominium and shopping mall complex, the latest wonder of the age. The citizens gritted their teeth in outrage, but could find no button to push or dial to turn that would save the old place. There were letters to the editor and a couple of abortive attempts to get a march happening, but everything fizzled out. And the developers did have one trump card: at a public meeting they presented the evidence that the municipal building inspectors had in fact condemned the old place. Whatever happened, Lander House was full of dry rot, termites and carpenter ants. Its tenure was up. It was time to join the mansions in the sky. Then a woman named Elsie Drapeau arrived from Ontario, where dirty old buildings which should have been scrapped years ago were being saved all the time. \ldblquote Lander House is a heritage building!\rdblquote  she cries \emdash  a new idea in a province where all buildings are torn down when they turn thirty. She proposes a Heritage Society, an idea enthusiastically approved by the locals, and in no time at all they are going full bore to Save Lander House. In the meantime, the developers (who hadn't been letting any grass grow under their bulldozers) formally give notice to the few remaining long-term residents and lay off the staff. A fence is erected 71 \page  around the property, and all the bulldozers, cranes and wrecking balls needed to demolish the place utterly, march enthusiastically in. Members of the Heritage Society announce their intention of sacrificing their bodies to the bulldozers. The developers state that it is unfortunate if the Heritage Society members wish to sacrifice their bodies, but if they insist, well, in a democracy they are certainly free to do so. As usual, the police are in the middle. So it is that The Tack and I find ourselves driving to Lander House at 6 a.m. It's a bitter cold morning in November. Sarge doesn't think we'll need back-ups today; he says it's unlikely that much will happen at the first confrontation, and that too many members being present might heat things up. \ldblquote If you need help, call,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote But don't expect much. We're short-handed and over-loaded. Try to cool things down on your own.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Five steps,\rdblquote  The Tack says to me. \ldblquote I don't know if they'll help us here,\rdblquote  I say glumly. \ldblquote It's a communications problem,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote Like any other. So, first \emdash  I get control of myself. Remember that these people are going to be hostile and fanatic. So I have to be the cool one. If I can stay cool, I can control the situation. If I get my feathers ruffled \emdash  and some of them will try for that \emdash  then I lose.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  I say. \ldblquote Second,\rdblquote  he continues, \ldblquote I listen. That's got to be active listening, not passive. I've got to ask questions and give feedback, so 72 \page  that both sides know that I really care about their positions, but also that I'm impartial.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  I say again. \ldblquote Third, I empathize. I have to let them know that I understand how they feel. As a matter of fact,\rdblquote  he says, turning to look at me, \ldblquote I do know how they feel. My brother-in-law drives a cat for the contractor and some of my wife's friends are charter members of the Heritage Society. So I hear lots from both sides.\rdblquote  \ldblquote When you empathize,\rdblquote  I caution, \ldblquote you have to be careful not to let them think you're also approving. Understanding how they feel doesn't mean you're choosing up sides.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  he agrees. \ldblquote Now, the hard part is Step Four. How the hell am I going to get them involved in stopping the confrontation when both sides are performing for the TV cameras? Hell, they want confrontation!\rdblquote  I nod. \ldblquote But,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote if we can do it, then we might not have to go on to Step Five. The last thing we want to do here is to act, right? No doing the chicken, no head-bopping. If we lay a baton alongside someone's head, we'll see it on the six o'clock news. And Billy Smart will be clucking away on Channel Four about police brutality again.\rdblquote  Speaking of Billy Smart, as we come up to Lander House there he is. His bright-coloured van with CHANNEL FOUR: FIRST WITH ALL THE NEWS on the side is parked at the entrance to the complex. His cameras and lights are all set up, ready for action. He sees us at the same moment we see him. He waves us over. The last time Billy Smart met Tacky Burns was one of those classic moments in a police officer's life that haunts us for our entire careers. Tacky was directing traffic around a particularly gruesome 73 \page  accident which took the lives of three teen-agers. Billy was there with his camera, trying to interview him. He was getting typical Tack responses \emdash  grunts and monosyllables. Finally Billy nailed him with, \ldblquote You don't seem to be very cooperative, Constable. Don't you think that the public has a right to know what's going on here?\rdblquote  Tacky fixed him with a sour look and responded, \ldblquote Why don't you just fuck off. What are you, some kind of ghoul? And no, the public don't have a right to the kind of shit that you put in your so-called news program. Now get your ass out of my way.\rdblquote  Billy bleeped it, aired it with great glee and ended with an editorial on how our taxes etc. etc. Billy leans out and grins as he recognizes Tacky. I\rquote ve never seen a more predatory look. He's literally licking his chops at the thought of his lead-off for tonight's Six O' Clock News. \ldblquote Well, well, well, if it isn't Constable Sharp-As-A-Tack-AndTwice-As-Dumb,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote Nice to see you again. Been directing any interesting traffic lately?\rdblquote  74 \page  He signals to the cameraman, who swings the big cyclops around to focus on us. Tacky smiles back and says, \ldblquote No, and I sure hope we never have to go through another tragedy like that again.\rdblquote  His face is open and sincere. \ldblquote What are you here for, Billy, and how can we help you?\rdblquote  \ldblquote I'm here to cover the battle between the developers and the Heritage Society,\rdblquote  Billy says. He sounds surprised at Tack's conciliatory attitude. \ldblquote Tell me, Constable, is there any truth to the story that you guys are bringing in the fire department?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Fire department?\rdblquote  Tack says innocently. \ldblquote What for?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Water cannon.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Water cannon? You mean hoses? Well. Where did you hear that, Billy?\rdblquote  Tacky asks. Billy waggles his arms. \ldblquote Reporters hear all kinds of things,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote So what about it? Are they coming?\rdblquote  I picture in my mind's eye the look on his face if Tacky uses the party line, No Comment. Instead, Tack purses his lips and looks wise. \ldblquote Well, now, Billy,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote I don't personally have any information on such a thing, though I can certainly see why it would be of considerable importance to you and your viewers. Let's think this thing out together. If the fire department was going to come in \emdash  where would they come from?\rdblquote  Billy says witheringly, \ldblquote From the fire department, dumbo. Where else?\rdblquote  75 \page  \ldblquote Yeah, that's right,\rdblquote  Tack says. \ldblquote You sure know your stuff, Billy. But which station? We have three in this town.\rdblquote  \ldblquote So you do expect them, then?\rdblquote  Billy says. \ldblquote Me? Naw. I'm just a cop doing his job. I don't know nothing about the fire department. You could call the Station, though,\rdblquote  he suggests helpfully. \ldblquote They might know something. Me, I'm just here to help folks talk to each other.\rdblquote  He looks at the construction site, where there might be some people stirring. \ldblquote But as you say, keep your eye on the road,\rdblquote  he says pleasantly, pointing south. \ldblquote You never can tell.\rdblquote  The funny part of the whole story is that the confrontation doesn't come off after all. The protesters get an injunction prohibiting the developers from actually demolishing any property for 24 hours, and so today nothing happens at all. (We don't know this at the time, of course, but eventually both sides will get together and manage to hack out an agreement. The developers will promise to keep the facade of the original building, so that there will be at least some of the flavour preserved of the old Lander House.) Today, however, Billy Smart is not happy. He doesn't have a story. So on the Six O' Clock News, there's the interview with Cst. Burns and me, two heroic police officers braving the elements to keep the developers and heritage people from killing each other. At the end, Billy's face swims into frame and he says, \ldblquote We tend to criticize our police too easily. Sometimes they are put in impossible situations, and it's easy for reporters to hold them up to ridicule. But on days like this, when they have nothing to work with but their frail bodies and their iron wills, it's impossible not to respect their courage.\rdblquote  76 \page  A bit overripe, perhaps \emdash  but a nice sentiment, right? Or as Tacky says the next day, when Sarge is telling us what a good job we did: \ldblquote Nothing to it. Just a simple communications problem. Follow the steps: control yourself \emdash  listen carefully \emdash  empathize \emdash  get 'em involved. If you do them right, you don't have to go to the final step and take action. It's funny \emdash  I planned to defuse the protesters and the developers but instead it worked just fine with the media. I used all those steps with Billy.\rdblquote  \ldblquote I can see how you controlled yourself and listened to him and showed empathy,\rdblquote  Sarge agreed. \ldblquote But how did you involve him?\rdblquote  Tacky smiles. \ldblquote I got him to watch out for the fire department for me.\rdblquote  77 \page  chapter eight aka 'tacky' AAll good things come to an end, and so eventually does my partnership with Tacky Burns. I take a desk job, and Tacky continues on general duties. But with a difference: now he's consciously practicing communication skills to improve his performance. Furthermore, he applies for, and takes, every course he can find. In the old days he turned up his nose at the classroom stuff, claiming that you couldn't beat \ldblquote The School of Hard Knocks\rdblquote  \emdash  but now he just can't seem to get enough training. He begins reading, too: good books like Born To Win, I'm OK \emdash  You're OK, and Boss Talk. In all this time, we don't lose touch. Both of us recognize the fact that there is something about our relationship that's different, special, and worth preserving. Tack and Marian ask me over for dinner. \ldblquote I've been talking to Sam,\rdblquote  I tell them over dessert. \ldblquote She says she might be willing to give things another try. She's moved out of the teacher's place and is thinking about coming home.\rdblquote  78 \page  \ldblquote Great news,\rdblquote  Tack says, his mouth full of lemon meringue pie. Marian nods enthusiastically. \ldblquote Yep,\rdblquote  I say. \ldblquote Teaching you communications skills got me to asking myself why I haven't used them myself \emdash  where it counts, you know? I mean, if they work on the job, why not at home?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah, why not?\rdblquote  he agrees. He turns and looks at Marian. \ldblquote This is great pie,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote Oh...it's nothing,\rdblquote  she says, but I can see she's pleased. \ldblquote No, it is something,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote Absolutely terrific.\rdblquote  And he touches her on the arm. As she goes into the kitchen he looks at me. \ldblquote I've been doing it too,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote Remember the night we talked in the car \emdash  about paying more attention and giving recognition? \emdash  well, I decided to try it.\rdblquote  He gets up and starts clearing the table. Tacky clearing the table? This is a whole new animal, I tell myself as I help him take the plates into the kitchen. Marian looks at him affectionately as he dries the dishes, and I realize that this isn't an act put on for my benefit \emdash  this is the way things actually are between them now. I watch him and make some mental notes for my possible reunion with Sam. How about this, I marvel: the student is teaching the teacher! 79 \page  Later, Marian is putting the kids to bed and The Tack and I are having a cigar out on the front porch. \ldblquote You know,\rdblquote  he says, \ldblquote you really did change my life, Matt.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah?\rdblquote  \ldblquote I used to be such a jerk. All my values were upside down. I'm still no great shakes, but I'm a different guy from what I used to be.\rdblquote  I nod in the darkness. \ldblquote I used to think that I had to prove what a big man I am. So I did a lot of drinking at choir practice and hassled civilians all the time. I never realized what a stupid moron I was.\rdblquote  \ldblquote I'm a bigger one than you,\rdblquote  I say. \ldblquote I couldn't even keep my marriage going.\rdblquote  \ldblquote But,\rdblquote  he goes on, \ldblquote once I started actually using The System \emdash  and discovered that it actually works \emdash  my life changed. Damn it, Matt, I was the most skeptical and cynical member you ever met, and if I can buy what you're selling, why doesn't everybody?\rdblquote  I don't answer. I don't have an answer for that question. After a while, Tack starts again: \ldblquote Did I ever tell you how I got my nickname?\rdblquote  \ldblquote I asked you about it once, but you told me to mind my own business.\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yeah, well, that was then and this is now.\rdblquote  He pauses such a long time that I think he's changed his mind, but finally he says in a low voice: 80 \page  \ldblquote It was my first month on the job. Long before I transferred here. My trainer was Dozer Dempster \emdash  ever hear of him?\rdblquote  I knew about Dozer, all right. He was a terminal case of ABS \emdash  Asshole Burnout Syndrome. He was a genuine dinosaur, a hold-over from a bygone age. When our new sergeant took over a couple of years ago, his very first act was to facilitate Dozer\rquote s early retirement. \ldblquote Dozer always used to get assigned to recruit training in those days because his bosses went nuts trying to find work that he wouldn't screw up,\rdblquote  Tacky says. \ldblquote They figured that recruit training was something he could do, for Chrissake. And every recruit who went through his hands was crippled for the rest of his career. Including me. \ldblquote Well, one night we \emdash  Dozer and me \emdash  answer a call to a place on Fourth Street where some old fella had died. Dispatch was kinda vague about just what the problem was, except to say that the people there were hysterical. The coroner had been, and a couple of our boys had checked it out, but now there was some kind of a problem and they wanted the police. \ldblquote So we go into this old three-story house and find a whole raft of folks in an uproar in the living room. They're bouncing off the walls, for Chrissake. There's a couple guys from Dillon's Mortuary Services standing against the wall, and two steroidal weight lifters (who I later find out are the grandsons of the deceased) putting the arm on them. \ldblquote And there's a gurney with a stiff on it head-first in the fireplace. \ldblquote What had happened, Matt, was this. Gramps dies in an upstairs bedroom. The family call the funeral parlour, who send out two guys and a hearse. The two guys take their gurney and go up the stairs to where the old geezer is lying. 81 \page  \ldblquote Now, you gotta see the picture here, Matt. Gramps is from a time warp, for Chrissake. He's got a big white beard, a fat round little belly like a bowlful of jelly, and he's wearing red long johns. You know, what they used to call a union suit \emdash  complete with trap door in the rear. \ldblquote The two guys from the funeral parlour loaded Gramps on the gurney and started to try to manoeuvre him down the narrow stairs. \ldblquote They got him as far as the second landing when the guy at the bottom end of the gurney tripped and fell backwards, yanking it out of the hands of the guy at the top. The gurney, which was on wheels, took off on its own. It bumped its way down the stairs, across the hallway and into the living room where the grieving family watched astounded as Gramps crashed headlong into the fireplace, releasing a fine shower of soot.\rdblquote  He stops. \ldblquote Go on,\rdblquote  I prod. \ldblquote The two steroids put a citizens arrest on the two mortuary guys, for Chrissake, and call the police,\rdblquote  Tacky continues. \ldblquote The police \emdash  that's Dozer and me \emdash  we prance into the living room. The family rant their story to us about clumsy stiff-collectors and demand action. And that's when I get my nickname.\rdblquote  \ldblquote What the hell did you do?\rdblquote  I ask. \ldblquote It's not what I did \emdash  it's what I said.\rdblquote  \ldblquote So, what did you say, then?\rdblquote  Tack hesitates. Suddenly he's not so anxious to finish his yarn. But after a while he goes on: \ldblquote I look at the Gramps in the fireplace,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote This old elf in his red long johns and his white beard and his fat little belly like a bowlful of jelly. And then I look at the members of the family, sitting around grieving. And I just can't help it. Out come the words \emdash  Santa came early this year, eh? 82 \page  \ldblquote Well, old Dozer starts to laugh, and he can't stop. He rolls on the floor. One of the grandsons quits doing his citizen\rquote s arrest long enough to go to the phone and call the PD to send two more cops to arrest the ones they already sent, for Chrissake. You can imagine what the Sarge had to say to Dozer and me when we got back.\rdblquote  I'm laughing myself, maybe harder than Dozer did. When I get control I ask, \ldblquote But what about the name? How did you get \lquote Tacky\rquote  out of that?\rdblquote  \ldblquote It's what the Sarge said,\rdblquote  Tack murmurs in the darkness. \ldblquote The Sarge said: \lquote Constable Burns, that is absolutely the tackiest thing I ever heard an officer say\rquote .\rdblquote  His glowing cigar moves like a lightning bug. \ldblquote And that night at choir practice Dozer tells the story, and everybody starts calling me Tacky. Dozer tells the story five thousand times, for Chrissake, before I finally pop him one and tell him to shut his mouth about it.\rdblquote  We fall silent. Finally he says, \ldblquote I broke all the rules of The System. I didn't control myself, I didn't listen, and worst of all, I didn't give them any empathy. I certainly didn't give them any chance to become involved. There was gramps in the fireplace, and all I could do was make a bad joke out of it.\rdblquote  He stubs out his cigar and says, \ldblquote And you know, Matt, after all this time, I have to admit that Sarge was right. It was the tackiest thing any officer ever said.\rdblquote  83 \page  chapter nine the new coach AAfter three years of intensive personal growth, Tack is finally designated as a Recruit Field Trainer. Now he has his own recruit to train. I've always been a compulsive note-taker. Every chance I get, I listen in on what he's telling the new guy. I make a collection of his homilies, instructions, and advice. Lots of it is great stuff. It's all based on this one idea: that if you can get in and out in five minutes and defuse potential situations through intelligent communications, then most of your routine problems will blow away like dandelions in the fall. Any police officer will benefit from thinking about the concepts, tips and hints that Tack gives his recruit. These are real, genuine Tackyisms, folks! So...he-e-e-ere's Tack! 84 \page  1. police officers and doctors Police officers are like doctors: the really good ones don't do much. If possible, that is. A good doctor doesn't want to operate. He sees an operation as the last resort. He wants your bod to heal itself. So he says, \ldblquote Take an aspirin and call me in the morning.\rdblquote  A good police officer doesn't want to operate either. You don't want to draw your baton or your gun if you can help it. You just want people to take an aspirin and go home to sleep it off. 85 \page  The best way to avoid problems is to sit on your anger, listen carefully to what folks are saying and give them some empathy so they know you care. Those are the first three steps in The System. Good police officers and good doctors do those things. And most times it works. When it doesn't work, the doctor goes on to Step Four: Involvement. He talks the patient into curing himself, with diet or drugs. And finally, if he has to, he goes to Step Five, Act. He calls in a surgeon. It's the same way with cops. If people don't want to cool off and go home, then get them involved in helping you. This makes sense on two levels: they do things for you that you don't have time to do yourself; and when they're busy, they're out of your hair. If they won't cooperate, then you can play paddywhack on their patooties. 86 \page  2. civilians or clients? Some police officers seem to think that civilians are put on the earth just to bug them. How many times have I heard cops swearing about stupid jerks who left their cameras on the back seats of unlocked cars and then come wimping to us when they get swiped? Civilians! we think to ourselves, and treat them like snotbags. Well...when my car or my heart conks out I call a mechanic or a doctor. They're experts in cars and hearts. I'm not. I ask dumb questions, and I guess they think I've been stupid and didn't conduct proper maintenance on my car or my bod. But they don't tell me that. Likewise, we are the experts on crime. When people need crime experts, they call us. And if we think they act stupid or ask dumb questions, we shouldn't let on. Take the time, if you have it, to explain \emdash  so they aren't so stupid next time. That's called \ldblquote crime prevention\rdblquote . It keeps everybody happy, especially the boss. Like doctors and mechanics, we're professionals. We do keep our lips buttoned, no matter how people behave. 87 \page  One day I had my car towed into a busy garage. I said to the mechanic, \ldblquote Geez, I must be the last guy you want to see today, with so many cars lined up for repairs.\rdblquote  He said, \ldblquote Hey, man, that's the mark of success. Lots of cars in the lot means more beans on my table. No cars in the lot, we close down and I'm out of a job.\rdblquote  If I get a problem with my golf swing, and I go to the Pro, he doesn't think, \ldblquote This stupid jerk, he should have known better than to bend his left arm like that.\rdblquote  No, he's a professional. He sees me as a customer. The public doesn't know or care about our problems. Why should they? You don't worry about the mechanic's problems with late deliveries from the warehouse, do you? You don't fret because the doc's new inter-fragiscope hasn't arrived, do you? Course not! So why should we expect civilians to understand our concerns? So don't think of civilians as stupid jerks. Think of them as clients. Yes, we get too many files, we're overworked, it's a pain in the butt, but we are working. Sometimes we're even making overtime, and that pays for the rec room and the kids' teeth. Maybe we ought to be grateful for the booze and the jerks who abuse it: if civilians didn't screw up occasionally, we wouldn't have a job. 88 \page  3. barking dogs and other nuisances Recruits always want to get out there and do high speed chases, rescue kids from abusers, and save the world from the pushers and other bad guys. But the police experience isn't like Popeye Doyle or NYPD Blue. Those shows have to entertain the folks, so they always show lots of fights and shoot-ups. I mean, would you stay home on a Friday night to watch TV that shows real police officers answering boring routine calls about barking dogs and noisy neighbours? And then writing up the reports on well-used keyboards? Not bloody likely! \page  We join the force because we want an exciting job, but the truth is that most officers never fire their guns over their entire career (except to practice \emdash  when they can get ammo) and most of us don't want to. That makes it real hard to take these calls seriously. They just don't seem very important. I mean, when you are investigating a murder, how excited can you get when some old lady pensioner phones about a gaggle of raggedy teen-agers hanging around too near her corner? And when things are really busy \emdash  you got a hot lead on a drug case, you're trying to write a report on a fatal accident that left you itching to kill the drunk who plowed through a Sunday School picnic, there's an outbreak of burglaries, and the third suspicious fire of the week has just been reported \emdash  that's when the nuisance calls come. Well, bud, you have to answer them anyway. The only question is: Will the old lady feel that the officer gives a damn...or not? When she calls, her problem is The Big One, and unless you can walk in her shoes for a minute she'll never understand why you didn't rush right over to save her. Think about it. If you slough her off and give her the idea that she's a pain in the neck, what'll happen? At the very least, she'll badmouth the police. Can't you just hear her at her next tea party, saying, \ldblquote Well, girls!I called the police, just like they're always saying we should do, but I got a rude young man who couldn't wait to get me off the phone!\rdblquote  And then the next time she has a complaint, she won't call. She'll say, \ldblquote Well, they don't really want to hear from me.\rdblquote  And we miss that vital tip. 90 \page  So get into the habit of looking at each call as an opportunity, not as a nuisance. Even if all you do is build a little community support, it's still worth it. If you take the time to apply The System, you may create an ally and supporter for life. And more important to you personally, you may not have so many complaints about yourself. Not bad for five minutes work, eh? 91 \page  4. a ticket to ride Police officers play two different kind of parent roles to the public. Sometimes we nurture and save; and sometimes we punish and hurt. When we rescue trapped people or look after lost kids we're like a nurturing parent. But when we give people tickets for traffic violations we're the punishing parent. It's a lot like the noisy party problem: if we catch people doing something wrong, they start behaving like children. If they act like obedient children, we don't have a problem. We just issue the ticket, they accept it, and that's all there is to it. But sometimes they go into the rebellious child state, and that's when we need The System. Step One \emdash  controlling your own feelings \emdash  can be hard to do when some guy calls you a useless pig who ought to be out doing real police work instead of harassing honest citizens like etc. etc. etc. If you're having a hard day, and you feel like you're going to blow your top at the next guy who badmouths you, have a little chat with yourself before you leave your vehicle. Remember, the person you're about to nail is your bread and butter. The worse they are, the more control you're going to need. 92 \page  If you give in to your natural impulses and pop them a good one, they'll see you in court. And who's the winner then? Step Two is to listen. I know a couple of officers who do this in interesting ways: Cst. Ed Mills always says, \ldblquote Well, I guess you know why I stopped you, eh?\rdblquote  And the answers range from astonishment that Family Court in Ontario has tracked them down to an admission that they're carrying contraband in the trunk. Cst. Pat Murphy, on the other hand, tries to get more than one violation on the burner. His approach sounds something like this: \ldblquote Hey, buddy, you were speeding, you did a rolling stop and you aren't wearing your seat belt. But you look like a responsible citizen. I tell you what, I'll give you a break: I'll just issue a ticket on the speeding. But if you cause any trouble around here in the next few days, I'll give the other two. What do you say?\rdblquote  The driver thanks him for the ticket. Politicians use this trick all the time, and we always fall for it. If they want to raise the cost of medicare premiums, for example, they announce that they're going to raise it by 40%. If the public screams, they say that they're \ldblquote listening to the people\rdblquote  and bring it down to 20% \emdash  which is what they intended all along. And the people thank them for it! What a crock! Step Three \emdash  empathize. There's nothing wrong with letting someone know that you understand how they feel. I always try to find out why they did the violation in the first place, and I say something like, \ldblquote Yeah, I know how it feels. It's no fun being bagged for something like this. Still, now that you've got it, you might as well learn something from it, eh?\rdblquote  Letting the other person blow off some steam could save somebody's life. If they are speeding because they\rquote re mad and you make 93 \page  them even madder, after you've left they just might drive away like they are on the Indy. But if you listen to their story, and let them know that you understand their feelings, they\rquote ll likely calm down and even accept the ticket with gratitude. They\rquote ll think to themselves, Well, at least the cop was decent about it. And I did deserve the ticket. I mean, what's wrong with a little basic PR? Step Four is to involve them. Maybe they need to think about ways they can improve their driving skills. Or maybe you should take a few minutes and guide them go through some scenarios so that when they goes home they\rquote ll have a half-decent chance of actually communicating with their mate. And Step Five is what you do when the other steps have failed. State that if they give you any more trouble in your territory you'll stuff their car so full of blue paper it'll be blowing out the windows. Tell them that if they can't be civil, you'll tell every officer in the detachment to be on the lookout for that red Ford. Tell them to get their brakes fixed \emdash  and the tail light, horn, and every other part of the car. Tell them you're not going to charge them for all these defects this time but if they draw themselves to your attention one more time \emdash  ka-boom! What the hell, you might as well have a little fun. 94 \page  5. you never can tell And it's not only calls that you can't tell about. It's also uninvited visitors. Let me tell you a story. A few months ago I was parked under a tree doing a surveillance. I was waiting for my partner to get back to me with a warrant to search Bill Butler's house \emdash  did you read about the bust in the papers? \emdash  and I didn't want the slug leaving town till we'd had a good look under his bed. While I'm waiting, one of Butler's neighbours comes up to my car. \page  \ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  he says, poking his head in the window. \ldblquote You're a cop, right? Whatcha doing here?\rdblquote  My first reaction is to punch the guy in the snoot. My second is to tell him to bug off. My third is to raise the window really fast and catch his nose in it while it's still poking into my business. But then I remember that the first rule of the The System is to get control of yourself so I just nod and say howdy. \ldblquote Come on,\rdblquote  he pushes, \ldblquote whatcha doing? You're watching Bill's house there? I always knew he was a bad one.\rdblquote  I don't tell him why I'm there, but I do let him talk to me about Butler (he doesn't have any real information, but how much does it cost me? A few minutes of my time, which isn't worth much anyways). I ask him some questions and empathize about the lousy condition of the road. And he goes away feeling good. My buddy gets back and we bust Butler's house. Would you believe he had a professional hydroponics operation in his basement capable of producing up to 150 plants at a time? A nice catch. But when I get back to the station I discover that I've lost a file. Now you know and I know that we aren't supposed to take files out of the station, and usually I never do, but I was behind in my work and I was trying to save a little time. I knew I was going to be doing surveillance, so I took a chance and brought a file to work on in the car. And in all the excitement, I must have let it slip out on to the ground when I opened the car door. Anyway, it's gone; and I'm drowning in a vat of sheep shit. And then, just as I'm going to walk into Sarge's office and confess all, who do you suppose treks in? 96 \page  It's Bill Butler's neighbour, the guy who filled my ear in the car! He calls me over and slips a large manila envelope into my hand. I open it: it's the missing file. \ldblquote I found this after you left,\rdblquote  he says. \ldblquote It looked important. I thought maybe you'd want it back right away. I put it in an envelope for you.\rdblquote  Can you imagine how I felt? So I thank the guy and mark up another win for The System. If I'd followed my first impulse \emdash  or my second or third, for that matter \emdash  he'd have turned the file in to Sarge or published it in the newspaper, cooking my goose either way. But because I controlled my irritation and took the trouble to chat with him, I still have a career in this outfit. All it cost me was a little self-control. Really, you never can tell. 97 \page  6. wild parties They're all drunk and disgusting. There's a guy passed out behind the sofa. Half-naked people are screaming and chasing each other around the living room. The stereo is cranked up to about a hundred and fifty decibels: your ears actually hurt. You can sure see (and hear) why the neighbours called the cops. Even though no real laws are being broken, except for the noise \emdash  no underages or coke, just a bunch of dumb drunks \emdash  your first temptation is to bust as many of them as you can and trot them all off to the tank. That's what you'd like to do \emdash  but you know that's the worst possible solution to the problem. Besides, even if what they're doing isn't your idea of a good time, you might be feeling just a touch of envy: they are doing their thing, after all, and maybe you'd like to be doing yours. What you really need to do is to get them to tone it down so the neighbours will stop complaining. Problem is...when you answer a call to a noisy soiree, all that the jerks see is your uniform. That's the symbol of authority. Right away they start to act like nasty little brats. They behave like they're back on the school playground, with you cast in the role of the teacher. I learned a lot of practical stuff about how people interact in sensitive situations from a book called Games People Play, by Eric Berne. Every officer should read it. It gives you tools for quick analysis 98 \page  of communications transactions between people, and ways of getting control. He says people behave in three different modes, which he calls PARENT, ADULT and CHILD. When we use our power to either nurture or punish other people, we are said to be in the PARENT state. Arresting someone, giving out a traffic ticket, and bringing a lost child back to the station are examples of the Parent state. When we are in a logical problem-solving mode, we are in the ADULT. Solving a crime, participating in a meeting, and developing a community project are examples of the Adult state. And when we are being emotional, we are said to be in the CHILD. Sulking, loving, losing our temper, ecstasy and despair are examples of the Child state. 99 \page  Booze limits our personalities. We go from Adult to Child pretty damn pronto. It's hard to be Adult when you're juiced. I should know \emdash  I've attended enough choir practices. And cops can skip from Adult to Child as fast as anyone I know. So when an officer (Parent) tries to talk to the party people (Child) it's like Daddy telling a bunch of noisy kids to pipe down. And what do noisy kids do when Daddy tells them to pipe down? They have two choices. They can (1) obey, or (2) tell him to blow it out his nose. The first one is the Obedient Child: the second is the Rebellious Child. If he's lucky enough to snag the Obedient Child, things settle down okay. No more trouble. But if he hooks the Rebellious Child, then Daddy has a problem. It's exactly the same thing with party animals. The behaviour patterns they learned in early childhood take over when they're bombed. If you confront them in the Parent state, and you're lucky enough to hook the Obedient Child \emdash  that part of them that does truly want to please authority \emdash  they'll apologize and shut up. But if you get the Rebellious Child, then you have to deal with open hostility. And for every one Obedient Child in this world to make our lives easier, there's five jerks to keep us in business. Trust me. So don't make deal with the jerks. When you go in, look for the leaders. They'll usually let you know who they are. Learn their names. Then get them off in a corner somewhere and ask them to help you. 100 \page  Use The System. Pay attention to them. Listen. Empathize (\ldblquote Yeah, I know, it sure is hard to control a bunch like this\rdblquote ). Then get them involved by inviting them to join you \emdash  first in the Adult state \emdash  then the Parent. To get them into the Adult state, ask them for their ideas on how to contain the situation. Confer and discuss on an equal level. Get them thinking. And then to conduct them into the Parent state, ask them to accept the responsibility of cooling things down. Let them know that you believe in their ability to control the group. These guys are a bit like Rodney Dangerfield \emdash  they'll do anything for a little respect. So give them some. What we're talking about here is doing things in order. Nine times out of ten the natural leaders at a party will cooperate just fine. They'll tell the party people to cool it, and they usually will. They can accept it more easily from their own, whereas if you try it they may see you as a Top Gun, someone they can prove their manhood against. We're looking at Step Four here \emdash  Involvement. If you can get the leaders involved in controlling the situation for you, then you can leave without having to arrest anyone. If this doesn't work \emdash  and it won't, sometimes \emdash  then you have to get into basic down-and-dirty police work. It's a matter of options, see. If you do the down-and-dirty first, you can't hop into the System later. Once the night sticks start flying it's too late to talk. 101 \page  Whereas if you try The System first and it fails, you do have something else to fall back on. They don't. If you give them a break and they don't take it, who looks good and who looks bad the morning after? Seems to me that it's better to have two strings to your bow than one. 102 \page  7. kids and parents There's a member I know who has a really insensitive streak in him. He doesn't understand how kids feel about police, or what long-term effects our behaviour has on them. Actually, I think he sees them as a nuisance to be tolerated, a pain in the ass. A couple of weeks ago I was with him in a mall when a woman pointed at him and said to her four-year-old, \ldblquote Now, that's a police officer. If you aren't a good boy, he'll come and put you in jail.\rdblquote  My friend the officer noticed this all right, but he didn't react. He just ignored her and kept on talking to me. 103 \page  In my opinion he might just as well have picked the kid up and held him at eye-level for about a minute, and when he's just about turning green, say, \ldblquote Yeah...and I hide in your closet at night, too. I'll jump out at you \emdash and grab you by your nose...and pull you inside out.\rdblquote  Now, he didn't say or do those things, but he might as well have. Kids are very literal. If his mother warns him about police officers right in front of one, and the member doesn't correct her, then the kid is entitled to assume that his mother is right. Right? I think my friend missed an opportunity. Not long ago this same police officer was searching a nineteen year old we knew was dirty when the kid's mom came out and started screeching at him. \ldblquote My kid is a good kid!\rdblquote  she rants. \ldblquote Lay offa him, you creep!\rdblquote  \ldblquote Listen, lady,\rdblquote  my friend the officer snarls, \ldblquote this kid sells more dope than a drugstore. One of these days he's gonna wind up in the slammer.\rdblquote  Well a couple of months later we bust the kid, and sure enough he draws six months. He graduates into the bigtime for sure. My friend runs into the kid's mom after the trial. \ldblquote See?\rdblquote  he tells her. \ldblquote I was right. What kind of parent are you, anyway? Why didn't you listen to me?\rdblquote  Well, why should she? His attitude was so negative and judgmental that it's not surprising she felt the way she did. He could have taken advantage of the situation and made a friend out of the kid's mother. He could have said, \ldblquote Hey, lady, I know how you feel. I got a kid the same age as your son. It's a real bummer, raising kids today. Let's talk about it.\rdblquote  104 \page  She might have confided in him. Maybe between them they could have turned the kid around. I know that we're not social workers, but do we have to go out of our way to make things worse? There's one thing you can say for this member, though. He's doing his bit to make sure that there'll be another generation of crooks and bums and dopers to keep the next generation of police in business. 105 \page  8. give them something to do In the movies, when the expectant father is flapping around getting in the way of the delivery, what does the doc do? The doc tells him to go boil some water. He doesn't say it because he needs hot water. He says it because he wants the new daddy to stop bugging him, so he can get on with his job. Police officers are in the same boat sometimes. It usually happens at an accident where some poor kid is stuck in a vehicle that has wrapped itself around a telephone pole at 3 a.m., and daddy is screaming at you to get his child out of there. You certainly understand how he feels, but it's hard to perform well through a barrage of verbal abuse. The best way to get him off your back so you can do your job is to give him some blankets to fold. If you don't have blankets, give the guy a flashlight and ask him to hold it for you. Or let him direct traffic. Or get him to search the ditch for something. The key is \emdash  get people involved. If they're riding a flashlight, they're not riding you. 106 \page  9. nok nok, who's there? Telling the next of kin that their dearly beloved has departed isn't a five minute job. It can take an hour or more. But it's the first five minutes of the interview that count. I remember one time when a call came in that a Wilhelm Adolf Holtz had been killed in an MVA in a neighbouring jurisdiction. I was detailed to inform his only daughter, Wilhelmina. In those days I hadn't learned to spend enough time in checking things out. I just assumed that the member who gave me the information was on the bit. So off I go to Wilhelmina's place. \page  She's having a party. I knock at her door and she looks blearily at me and says, \ldblquote Ossifer, are we making too much noise?\rdblquote  And I say, \ldblquote Are you Wilhelmina Holtz?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yup,\rdblquote  she says. \ldblquote That's me, Little Willy.\rdblquote  \ldblquote May I talk to you?\rdblquote  I say. She takes me through the living room into the kitchen. There I tell her gently that her father has died in an auto accident. She laughs! \ldblquote Not my dad,\rdblquote  she says. \ldblquote You got the wrong party. My dad's been dead for five years.\rdblquote  So I ask to use her phone. I call the dummy who gave me the information in the first place, and he says, \ldblquote Oh, sorry about that. Did I say father? I meant brother.\rdblquote  Since then I always ask a lot of questions, and check back to make sure I got it all straight. There are eight steps in doing a professional NOK: 1. RESEARCH. Make sure you got all the facts, and that you got them straight. How did the person die? Where? When? Be ready to answer their natural questions. And find out if there's any close friend or pastor who can come with you and stay with the bereaved after you've gone. 2. ALLIES. If the close friend or pastor is known to you, and 100% responsible, you can delegate the task. Let them do it instead of you. But at least see who you can get to go with you. 108 \page  3. GET INSIDE. Don't try to talk on the porch or through a screen door. Above all, don't do it on the phone (\ldblquote Hello, is this the Widow Black?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Yes, but I'm not a widow.\rdblquote  \ldblquote You are now!\rdblquote ). How do you get in? Simple \emdash  just ask. Say, \ldblquote Mrs. Black, I'm Constable Sympathy. I have an important matter to discuss with you. May I come in?\rdblquote  4. SIT DOWN. Don't loom over the poor soul. You're six foot seven and she's five foot two. Get on the same eye-level to reduce your impact. 5. TELL THEM. You have to figure the other person out to see what's the best way of spilling the bad news. If they ask you outright to give it to them, do it. \ldblquote Mrs. Black, I'm sorry to have to tell you that your husband, John, was fatally injured in an auto accident.\rdblquote  But if they want to beat around the bush, respect their wish. Let them lead the conversation till they ask you why you're there. 6. BE PREPARED. People are unpredictable under the stress of high emotions. I've had people run out into the night, try to shoot themselves, put their hands over their ears so as not to hear what I have to say, and even offer to beat me up. It's the old story of the king's messenger \emdash  if you don't like his message, off with his head. Be ready for anything. C.Y.A. 7. ADVISE. They may ask you what they should do next. You should be able to tell them. 109 \page  8. EXIT. Don't leave till the situation is under control. Make sure that friends or neighbours are there to support the bereaved person. The fact is that there are hardly any cases where people have complained about us for doing an insensitive job on an NOK. But that doesn't mean that we should be careless about it. I mean, after all, we do have to sleep nights, right? 110 \page  chapter 10 afterword: seven years later im Burns has done well. In the seven years since my last entry in this journal, he has been promoted and is now working as aJTraining NCO. 111 \page  Sam and I drop in from time to time to see how he and Marian are getting on. They have a splendid house in the suburbs. His son will be graduating from high school this year, his daughter is showing distinct talent in ballet, and Marian's going to the Institute of Technology to become a computer programmer. He himself has already taken some night school courses and tidied up his grammar. Would you believe, he sounds like a professor. He talks better than my Dad. He has a dynamite career ahead of him. And no one calls him 'Tacky' any more. The End 112 \page  acknowledgements TThe stories in this book, (which, though masked for obvious reasons, were all true) were supplied in large part by the members and support staff of the Gibsons Detachment., R.C.M. Police Without them, this book would never have been written. Thanks to \emdash  Members: Sgt. Ed Hill; Cpl. Bruce Waite; Constables Cliff Moss, Derek Crawford, Mark Wickson, Rick Sach, Mark Sorokan, Dennis Donaldson, Sean Bourrie, and Pat Murphy. Support staff: Sam Macey and Jeanne Hill. Guards, Mat